This is an excellent horror game that captures the pure essence of horror almost perfectly ( at least for me ) there is one time the game doesn't tell you what to do that's why its not 5 stars but you should cut the devs some slack. There are two roles you can play as a journalist and a junior detective the only differences are a few dialog options and how willingly the characters are going to share information. The true ending is challenging but tests your puzzle skills and the reward is great.

This game is actually AWESOME. Might be five bucks but it is TOTALLY worth it. The mystery of who took the deal is fun to unravel, and the little scares (like when you open Maya's case file for the first time) are extremely well placed and the cards are truly a work of aesthetic horror. There's also little jokes and humor to make sure you have a little fun instead of the game being nothing but from and dark. Would rate 10/10 if possible, you guys are great.

It definitely isn't as good as the first one, but it's still enjoyable and you definitely have to hunt for information if you really want to get all the details. Being as it's a sequel it's probably wise they dialed down the horror since you know what you're dealing with. I really enjoyed the first but it was definitely more rooted in horror whereas this one felt much more like a good pulp drama and was generally more "fun", and expanded the world a bit more. Only issue really is that the UIs and interaction somehow felt a little less polished and feel slightly more clunky but otherwise I'm looking forward to more in the series.

I appreciate the gameplay improvements over Simulacra 1, but the depth of gameplay seems to have been hurt by the overall increase in production value. SIM and Simulacra 1 felt sinister, while Pipe Dreams and Simulacra 2 both feel sanitized and campy. You don't seem to need to dive as deep here, which is great for getting though the game, but lacks the horror feel the previous games had. If there is a 3, I hope it combines 1's darkness and unpredictability with 2's checkpoints with less RNG.

And I wish for the good ending there was more opportunity to talk to the Simulacra. But I overall really enjoyed the whole experience.

Like its predecessors (SIM, Simulacra and Pipe Dreams), Simulacra 2 has great potential as a story telling game in the line of other "found phone" games. Unfortunately, immersion is the only way that found phone games can work, and it's entirely broken in Simulacra 2 by the litany of bugs and broken mechanics. After roughly 20 minutes, the phone controls stopped responding, making the game unplayable. That was enough right there for me to regret paying for the game.
